                <note rend="inline" type="source">493.11/829: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-06-23T09:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 23, 1922—9 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 23—3:47 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>280. In note dated June 19th Minister for Foreign Affairs declares that it will
                    be very difficult to resume payments Boxer indemnity<note n="77"
                        xml:id="d596fn77">For five-year postponement of Boxer indemnity payments,
                        see <ref target="frus1917Supp02v01#pg_685">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1917, supp. 2, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, pp. 685</ref> ff.</note> and “there appears
                    to be no alternative but to again request an extension of two years”. Says, <pb
                        facs="0930" n="810" xml:id="pg_810"/>
                    <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“When financial conditions are somewhat easier an arrangement can then be
                            arrived at by consultation.</p>
                        <p>We believe that the American Government, which entertains the most
                            friendly feelings and has always been very sincere toward China, seeing
                            the stringent state of China’s finances, will believe in us and pardon
                            us for our action.</p>
                        <p>I have the honor to send you this note and to request that you will be so
                            good as to communicate with your Government requesting its approval
                            thereto.</p>
                        <p>I have the honor to ask that I be favored with a reply.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
